# Target Queries · AI Visibility Monitor

> Five buyer queries. The script queries each one monthly and records whether your domain is cited.
> Edit this file to change which queries are tracked. Keep it at 5 for focus. One query per line, no numbering, no quotes.

example query about your category
specific buyer query in your geography
category-defining term you are trying to own
product-specific query for your niche offering
industry-specific buyer search

## Rules for picking queries

- **Buyer language, not keyword language.** Write what your ICP would actually type into Claude or Perplexity, not what a keyword tool thinks.
- **Three-clicks-deep.** Each query should be something a buyer types after they already know what category they want. Generic terms have too much competition; specific terms are where you can win.
- **One geo query.** Anchor a local signal if your business has a geographic angle. Skip if you're remote/global.
- **One category-defining query.** A term you are trying to own as a category. Even if you are not cited today, tracking it monthly tells you when you start to appear.
- **One product-specific query.** A niche where you have a real differentiated offering.

## When to change this list

- Once a query is consistently cited at position 1-3 for three months in a row, retire it and add a new target.
- If a query is cited zero times for six months and competitor content is clearly better positioned for it, replace it.
- If your positioning changes (new vertical, new service), update the list the same week.

Log every change in git/commit history so the monthly JSON files stay interpretable against the query set that was active at that point in time.
